"{\"uid\": \"si.com-golf-wyndham-clark-seeks-olympic-redemption-paris\", \"text\": \"SAINT QUENTIN-EN-YVELINES, France \\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094 Three former U.S. Open champions are in the field for the men\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Olympic Golf Tournament. But not the most recent one.  In fact, Bryson DeChambeau has won two of the past five U.S. Opens and\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094although he would have played in Japan in 2021 but was forced out due to COVID-19\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s not at Le Golf Nationalfor the start of the tournament Thursday.  Wyndham Clark is and it\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s easy to suggest that DeChambeau is more deserving, certainly based on recency bias.  DeChambeau finished in the top six in three major championships this year; Clark missed the cut in three. In the one major where Clark made the cut\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094the U.S. Open\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094DeChambeau was the winner.  It is under that backdrop that Clark arrived outside of Paris looking to get back to the form he showed earlier this year when he won at Pebble Beach and contended at both the Arnold Palmer Invitational and Players Championship\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094finishing second at both to Scottie Scheffler.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s been a unique year,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Clark said Wednesday in advance of the tournament. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI started out fantastic and in previous years on Tour, I typically have kind of played better at the end or the year.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cBut I kind of have some injuries I have been dealing with, happened right before Houston leading into the Masters, and I have not been the same. I feel like I am finally getting to where I can swing at the level that I know I can swing, and so that's kind of been an ongoing issue and it's been frustrating for me.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cThen I have got to be honest, I have been very frustrated with how I played at the majors. I believe that I wasn't showing how good of a player I know I can be, and especially at highest level in the majors. But I have also got to look at how far I have come in two years. I am fifth on the FedEx in back-to-back years and I have won multiple times and I have a lot of top finishes and I am here at the Olympics.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cSo I have got to make sure I do not let the outside people put too much pressure on myself because I have grown so much in these two years. It's not where I want to be in the future, but years like this, I have learned a lot and I am hoping I take all the things I learned and play better in the majors next year.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  The other U.S. Open champions in the field are Spain\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Jon Rahm (2021) and England\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Matt Fitzpatrick (2022). Clark won last year at Los Angeles Country Club and added the victory earlier this year at Pebble Beach.  Clark was never really in big danger on missing out on the Olympics. Despite his poor form in the majors, he had those high finishes at Bay Hill and the Players. He tied for third at the RBC Heritage. That pushed him high enough in the rankings that he was able to stay among the top four Americans through the U.S. Open.  It was Collin Morikawa who was sweating it out. The two-time major winner won in the fall at the Zozo Championship but was battling for his Olympic spot through the U.S. Open, edging Patrick Cantlay for the final position at the end of the qualifying deadline which came via the Official World Golf Ranking.  Morikawa finished tied for 14th at the U.S. Open. Cantlay needed a two-way tie for second at the U.S. Open\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094basically one shot\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0094and finished third to finish behind him and out of the Olympics.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cWhen I look at it and compare right where I am now to where I was in January and February and March, there is been a lot of big wins,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Morikawa said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI have worked my ass off to get here and just because I made it does not mean it's over and does not mean I am getting my paddles back.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cI have been here before (at the 2021 Olympics), and I know what it feels like to honestly lose in a playoff for Bronze and that sucks. There is a lot of motivation just pushing yourself to come out and play some really good golf.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Morikawa was in the final group with Scheffler at the Masters before finishing tied for third and he tied for fourth at the Masters, playing with Schauffele in the final group  He was also tied for fourth at the Scottish Open before tying for 16th\\u00c2\\u00a0at the British Open.  Clark tied for ninth at the Travelers and tied for 10th at the Scottish with a strong final round, then missed the cut at Royal Troon.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cEver since the Masters, I have not been able to get up to the speed that I normally have with driver and I have been hitting it a lot shorter,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Clark said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt's been a lot of things where it led me down a path of, is it something in my swing, is it equipment, and then come full circle, we just realize now I am a lot healthier, and maybe there was a couple equipment things.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cBut you start going down rabbit holes that maybe I should not have gone down and next thing you know, I am missing cuts by a little bit and not playing at the level that I was earlier in the year or some parts of last year.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Clark said he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s gotten a boost playing with Scheffler as his partner in practice rounds against Schauffele and Morikawa.  He\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s also soaked up the experience, arriving for and taking part in the Opening Ceremony. He said he\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s attended at least one Olympic event per night through Tuesday, including gymnastics.  \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cFor me it only inspires you to see how hard they work, and they come to this moment,\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d Clark said. \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cIt's amazing that they excel under the lights when they have to. I really appreciate what they do and inspired, to be honest.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d  Loading recommendations... Please wait while we load personalized content recommendations  Bob Harig is a senior writer covering golf for Sports Illustrated. He has more than 25 years experience on the beat, including 15 at ESPN. Harig is a regular guest on Sirius XM PGA Tour Radio and has written two books, \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cDRIVE: The Lasting Legacy of Tiger Woods\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d and \\u00e2\\u0080\\u009cTiger and Phil: Golf\\u00e2\\u0080\\u0099s Most Fascinating Rivalry.\\u00e2\\u0080\\u009d He graduated from Indiana University where he earned an Evans Scholarship, named in honor of the great amateur golfer Charles (Chick) Evans Jr. Harig, a former president of the Golf Writers Association of America, lives in Clearwater, Fla.  \\u00c2\\u00a9 2026ABG-SI LLC-SPORTS ILLUSTRATED IS A REGISTERED TRADEMARK OF ABG-SI LLC. - All Rights Reserved. The content on this site is for entertainment and educational purposes only. Betting and gambling content is intended for individuals 21+ and is based on individual commentators' opinions and not that of Sports Illustrated or its affiliates, licensees and related brands. All picks and predictions are suggestions only and not a guarantee of success or profit. If you or someone you know has a gambling problem, crisis counseling and referral services can be accessed by calling 1-800-GAMBLER.\"}"